  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Passive Voice (الفعل المجهول)",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل المجهول",
      "content": [
        "The passive voice (المبني للمجهول) is used when the doer of the action is unknown or unimportant. In Arabic, the verb form changes by modifying its vowels.",
        "For the past tense Form I verb (فَعَلَ), the passive pattern is فُعِلَ - the first vowel becomes dammah and the second becomes kasrah."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Past tense: فَعَلَ → فُعِلَ (e.g., كَتَبَ → كُتِبَ)",
        "Present tense: يَفْعَلُ → يُفْعَلُ (e.g., يَكْتُبُ → يُكْتَبُ)",
        "The subject of a passive verb is called نائب الفاعل (deputy of the subject)",
        "نائب الفاعل is always مرفوع (nominative case)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كُتِبَ الْكِتَابُ", "english": "The book was written" },
        { "arabic": "فُتِحَ الْبَابُ", "english": "The door was opened" },
        { "arabic": "يُقْرَأُ الْقُرْآنُ", "english": "The Quran is read" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Passive with Feminine and Plural Subjects",
      "titleArabic": "المبني للمجهول مع المؤنث والجمع",
      "content": [
        "The passive verb agrees with its subject (نائب الفاعل) in gender and number, just like active verbs."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Feminine: أُرْسِلَتِ الرِّسَالَةُ (The letter was sent)",
        "Plural: كُتِبَتِ الْكُتُبُ (The books were written)",
        "The original object becomes the subject in the passive"
      ]
    }
  ],
